README.md — CSS Color Markers Exercise

Author: William Hullinger
Project: Colored Markers
Purpose:
This exercise demonstrates how CSS colors work in real-world scenarios.
It shows how different color systems (RGB, HEX, HSL), transparency, gradients,
and shadows are used together to create depth, realism, and reusable components.

================================================================

1. WHAT THIS EXERCISE IS ABOUT

This project is not about drawing markers.
It is about learning how color works in CSS through a simple visual object.

By building the same object three times with different color systems,
you learn how each system behaves and when to use it.

This mirrors how color is handled in real projects:
one component, multiple visual variants.

================================================================

2. CORE CONCEPTS DEMONSTRATED

This exercise demonstrates:

- Using color intentionally, not randomly
- Applying gradients to simulate light and depth
- Using shadows to separate elements from the background
- Using transparency to layer colors
- Reusing structure while changing appearance
- Understanding multiple CSS color formats

================================================================

3. STRUCTURE OF THE COMPONENT

Each marker follows the same structure:

- A base marker body
- A cap section
- A sleeve (label) section

The HTML uses:
- One base class: marker
- One modifier class: red, green, or blue

This pattern is extremely common in real-world development:
base component + variant class.

================================================================

4. COLOR SYSTEMS USED (INTENTIONAL)

Each marker uses a different color system on purpose.

RED MARKER
- Uses RGB for gradient colors
- Uses RGBA for the shadow
- Demonstrates numeric color control and opacity

GREEN MARKER
- Uses HEX colors
- Uses HEX with alpha for shadow opacity
- Demonstrates design-tool-friendly color values

BLUE MARKER
- Uses HSL for gradient colors
- Uses HSLA for the shadow
- Demonstrates how hue, saturation, and lightness affect color perception

Seeing these side by side helps reinforce how each system works.

================================================================

5. WHY GRADIENTS ARE USED

Flat colors look artificial.
Gradients simulate light hitting a round object.

Each marker uses:
- Dark color on the edges
- Brighter color in the center

This creates the illusion of a cylindrical shape.
This same technique is used in buttons, cards, and modern UI components.

================================================================

6. WHY SHADOWS MATCH THE COLOR

Each marker’s shadow is tinted to match its base color.

This matters because:
- Neutral black shadows can look dirty or flat
- Colored shadows feel more natural and intentional
- Real UI components often use color-aware shadows

Shadows are not decoration.
They communicate depth and separation.

================================================================

7. WHY TRANSPARENCY IS USED

Transparency is used in two places:

- The sleeve background
- The shadows

RGBA and HSLA allow layers to blend naturally.
This is critical in modern UI design where elements overlap.

================================================================

8. COLOR THEORY CONNECTION

This exercise reinforces key color theory principles:

- Neutrals are the foundation
- Color is used sparingly and purposefully
- Lightness changes communicate interaction and depth
- Consistency matters more than creativity

If every element were bright,
nothing would stand out.

================================================================

9. REAL-WORLD APPLICATIONS

The same techniques shown here apply to:

- Buttons with different variants
- Badges and status indicators
- Cards and panels
- Design systems and component libraries
- Theming and dark mode

This is not toy knowledge.
It directly maps to professional frontend work.

================================================================

10. HOW TO EXPERIMENT FURTHER

To continue learning, try:
- Changing only lightness values in HSL
- Adjusting gradient direction
- Softening or strengthening shadows
- Converting RGB values to HSL
- Replacing hard-coded colors with CSS variables

Make one change at a time and observe the result.

================================================================

FINAL TAKEAWAY

Good color usage is controlled, consistent, and intentional.
This exercise shows how CSS color systems are tools,
not magic.

Understanding when and why to use each one
is what separates beginners from professionals.

END OF FILE
